ect are •to prove that it is possible to design a structured fund in which investing in science can generate statistically reliable and attractive returns •to detail how a megafund to support biomedical research would need to be structured in order to match researchers’ and investors’ interests •to define the roles that different stakeholders need to play in this market in order to achieve the objectives mentioned above our ultimate goals are to offer a realistic solution to this challenge to design a new mechanism to raise new pools of funds for science and to prove that structured finance can play a role in finding answers to some of the problems facing humankind research publications fagnan david n nora yang john c mckew and andrew w lo  financing translation analysis of the ncats rarediseases portfolio science translational medicine   ps lo andrew w carole ho jayna cummings and kenneth s kosik  parallel discovery of alzheimers therapeutics science translational medicine   fagnan david austin gromatzky roger m stein josemaria fernandez and andrew w lo  financing drug discovery for orphan diseases drug discovery todaydownload software lo andrew w and sourya naraharisetti  new financing methods in the biopharma industry a case study of royalty pharma inc journal of investment management   fagnan david josemaria fernandez andrew w lo and roger m stein  can financial engineering cure cancer american economic review papers  proceedings   fernandez josemaria roger m stein and andrew w lo  commercializing biomedical research through securitization nature biotechnology  download software faq see more research publications ongoing research a portfolio approach to translational medicine a case study of ncats austin gromatzky andrew w lo manita singh and nora yang optimal capital structure risk and rd decisions theory and evidence from the pharmaceutical industry richard thakor and andrew w lo media video vikas p sukhatme  a simple onetime inexpensive and nontoxic intervent